    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-11-19T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-11-19T13:00:00-05:00" n="178"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d178">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">600.0012/11–1951: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Secretary of State to the Acting Secretary of State</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret   priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-11-19T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 19, 1951—7 p. m</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2994. Eyes only for Hickerson and Chase from Arneson. No further distribution.
                    Subject: Disarmament. To forestall any adverse comment from Baruch<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d178fn1">Bernard M. Baruch, New York financier; United States
                        Representative on the United Nations Atomic Energy Commission, 1946.</note>
                    re disarmament debates in <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>, Secy concurs in
                    suggestion made by Jessup and Arneson that Chase on strength of previous
                    association reassure Baruch US stands firm on <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>
                    plan as basis for internatl control to ensure prohibition atomic weapons.
                    [Arneson.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
